					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">If your going to create a new variable: think about making it #$ff when your character is standing somewhere, #$00 when he/she is falling, and #01 when rising.  That way you don't have to load another variable to find out if your player character is standing. <br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda new_variable<br />bmi ++<br />beq +fall<br />; this would be code for rising or jumping<br />;followed by a branch (a jump) to ++<br />+fall<br /><br />++</div><br /> And if your player character is rising and you want to make him or her fall just <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">dec new_variable</tt>. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />  I was guided to do something like this!  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_mrgreen.gif" alt=":mrgreen:" title="Mr. Green" /> Want to pass it along. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> <br /><br />Your logic seems well thought out. For me, I've not created many new variables because being guided to look at trace log files usually helps a solution be found that utilizes the variables that already exist (if not creating something new). <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />edit: did not change much; just removed one word <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

					
